From 5948f4a653e8cf821208c69988725bd2a2138cb7 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 19:46:45 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix timezone bug shifting units into the wrong month + add
 edge auto-scroll

Root cause of "I have to drop in November to get it into October": every
place that read productionMonth did `format(new Date(isoString), ...)`.
The backend always stores productionMonth as UTC midnight on the 1st
("2026-11-01T00:00:00.000Z"). new Date() parses that as UTC, but
date-fns format() renders in LOCAL time by default - so in any timezone
behind UTC (all of North America), that UTC midnight rolls back to the
previous day, which crosses the month boundary and silently displays/
buckets the unit under the WRONG month. This affected every month
display in the app, not just drag-and-drop: the calendar's grouping
logic, the drop no-op check, the search results dropdown, and Manager
Dashboard's production month column were all affected.

Fixed with a parseMonthSafe() helper that builds the Date directly from
the numeric year/month extracted from the ISO string, bypassing UTC
parsing entirely - added to both production-calendar and
manager-dashboard. Also fixed the Shipping-Date-derived guessedMonth
calculation, which had the same round-trip risk on the 1st of a month
specifically.

Also added edge auto-scroll during drag: dragging a card within ~90px
of the left/right edge of the calendar now automatically slides the
6-month window one month further (with a cooldown so it doesn't
runaway-scroll), making months further out - like December when
starting from a June view - reachable without cancelling the drag to
click the arrow buttons. Required removing stopPropagation() from the
per-card/placeholder dragover handlers so the edge-detection at the
container level still fires while hovering over a card near the edge.
